        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Jan 6. 80</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>It has gratified me much that you should have thought of sending me a copy of your ‘Souvenirs Entomologiques &amp;c’.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> In one sense I am worthy of the gift, for I do not believe that any one in Europe has more truly admired your investigations than I have done.<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I look forward with much pleasure to reading your volume, &amp; remain | With great respect | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/></p>
<p rend="left">Mons. Fabre</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">CD’s annotated copy of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_10935.xml">Fabre 1879</ref> is in the Darwin Library–CUL; see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12398.xml">letter from J.-H. Fabre, 3 January 1880</ref>. </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD described Fabre as an ‘inimitable observer’ in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 1: 364. See also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6019.xml"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref> 6th ed., pp. 216, 394.</note>
            
            
        </div>
    
